text:
76 Washington Square South (formerly 290 4th Street) at the S.W. corner of Wooster Street (Washington Square East). This is supposed to be the oldest house now standing on Washington Square. Washington Square South is part of 4th Street as originally laid out. In 1833, when 4th Street absorbed Asylum Street in Greenwich Village, the whole was renumbered from the northwest end at Gansevoort and 13th Streets. About 1860 the section from MacDougal to Wooster Streets was given its own house numbers as Washington Square South. October 4, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.
title: Manhattan: Washington Square South - Wooster Street

text:
113-117, 121-123 Bleecker Street, north side, at and west across Wooster Street. Nos. 115 and 117 are the two old houses with dormer windows. This is part of that section of Bleecker Street, from Broadway to Hancock Street, which was originally David Street. It was joined to, and assimilated by, Bleecker Street, as early as 1827 and probably by 1820.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Our Lady of Mercy Chapel (Roman Catholic) and a newly erected apartment building, 69-70 and 71 Washington Square South, between West Broadway and Wooster Streets.
February 12, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.
